# VAK_3b — VAkK_3.21

## Sanskrit — Devanāgarī

पूर्वक्लेशा दशाविद्या संस्काराः पूर्वकर्मणः ।
संधिस्कन्धास्तु विज्ञानं नामरूपमतः परम् ॥ VAkK_3.21 ॥

## Sanskrit — IAST

pūrvakleśā daśāvidyā saṃskārāḥ pūrvakarmaṇaḥ /
saṃdhiskandhās tu vijñānaṃ nāmarūpam ataḥ param // VAkK_3.21 //

## Padaccheda

| Sandhi form | Padaccheda | Basic meaning |
|---|---|---|
| pūrvakleśā | pūrva-kleśāḥ | former afflictions |
| daśāvidyā | daśa avidyā | the ten are ignorance |
| saṃskārāḥ | saṃskārāḥ | formations / conditioning activities |
| pūrvakarmaṇaḥ | pūrva-karmaṇaḥ | of former karma |
| saṃdhiskandhāḥ | saṃdhi-skandhāḥ | aggregates at the junction / linking aggregates |
| tu | tu | but / now |
| vijñānam | vijñānam | knowledge |
| nāmarūpam | nāma-rūpam | name-and-form |
| ataḥ param | ataḥ param | after this; thereafter |

## Literal Translation

The former afflictions are the tenfold ignorance; the formations are of former karma. But the aggregates at the junction are knowledge; after this is name-and-form.

## Philosophical Translation

In the prior section, the afflictive condition is summarized as ignorance, while the karmic condition is summarized as formations. At the junction into the present process, the linking aggregates are called knowledge; thereafter follows name-and-form.

## Technical Vocabulary

| Sanskrit | Working translation | Note |
|---|---|---|
| pūrva | former / prior | Refers to the prior limit from 3.20 |
| kleśa | affliction | Defiled motive-condition |
| avidyā | ignorance / non-principle | Opposite of vidyā; obstruction of discriminative knowing |
| daśa | ten | Refers to the ten kleśas treated as included under ignorance |
| saṃskāra | formation / conditioning formation | Here, karmic formation from prior action |
| karma | karma / action | Doctrinally tied to Chapter 4 |
| saṃdhi | junction / linkage | The transition point between prior and present becoming |
| skandha | aggregate | Canonically aggregate |
| vijñāna | knowledge | Not consciousness |
| nāmarūpa | name-and-form | Psycho-physical determination after the linking moment |

## Doctrinal Determination

VAkK_3.21 begins unpacking the twelve limbs introduced in 3.20.

It gives the first four positions:

```text
Prior limit:
    1. avidyā
    2. saṃskārāḥ

Middle:
    3. vijñāna
    4. nāmarūpa
```

But Vasubandhu's phrasing is important. He does not merely say:

```text
avidyā → saṃskāra → vijñāna → nāmarūpa
```

He says:

```text
former afflictions = ignorance
former karma = formations
junction-aggregates = knowledge
after that = name-and-form
```

So the verse is not only listing links. It compresses the prior-life causal mass into two formal determinations:

```text
kleśa
    → avidyā

karma
    → saṃskāra
```

Then it marks the present-life entry point:

```text
saṃdhi-skandha
    → vijñāna
```

The key term is saṃdhi: the junction, linkage, or transition. Vijñāna here is not general cognition. It is the linking knowledge at the threshold of the present embodiment.

## Logical Determination

The verse gives the first transition from past ground into present manifestation.

```text
Prior affliction
    ↓
Prior karma
    ↓
Junction knowledge
    ↓
Name-and-form
```

In logical terms:

```text
Avidyā
    = indeterminate non-principle / obscured ground

Saṃskāra
    = formed karmic determination

Vijñāna
    = junctional knowing, the first present mediation

Nāmarūpa
    = differentiated psycho-physical determinacy
```

So 3.21 is the first concrete answer to 3.20's abstract architecture.

3.20 says:

```text
2 / 8 / 2
```

3.21 begins filling it:

```text
avidyā / saṃskāra
        ↓
vijñāna / nāmarūpa
```

## Organon Interpretation

This verse is crucial because it shows that the world is not simply a spatial cosmology. It is a generated structure of appearance.

```text
Prior kleśa
    = corrupted principle

Prior karma
    = stored action-form

Junction knowledge
    = entry into present dataset

Name-and-form
    = first concrete schema of embodied appearance
```

In Organon terms:

```text
Avidyā
    = failure of principle

Saṃskāra
    = retained formative trace

Vijñāna
    = linking knowledge-event

Nāmarūpa
    = semantic embodiment
```

This means the present world begins not with matter, self, or substance, but with conditioned linkage:

```text
kleśa → karma → vijñāna → nāmarūpa
```

